canonical:
  title: 北山洛山寺贊
  author: 柳璥
  language: lzh
  text: 攝化髻中盛諸光明尋聲座側揷箇楊柳忽驚嶃角宛爾影形三土幾焦儻傾甘霔右寶甁臺佛香屍注元是同然五熏衆生妄興分別自有眞心徧攝大千牛頭栴檀眼中金屑右香爐峯
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 北山洛山寺贊
  author: 柳璥
  language: lzh
  text: |-
    攝化髻中。盛諸光明。尋聲座側。揷箇楊柳。忽驚嶃角。宛爾影形。三土幾焦。儻傾甘霔。
    右寶甁臺
    佛香屍注。元是同然。五熏衆生。妄興分別。自有眞心。徧攝大千。牛頭栴檀。眼中金屑。
    右香爐峯
korean:
  title: 북산 낙산사 찬
  author: 유경
  language: kor
  text: |-
    보병대(寶甁臺)조화를 지닌 육계(肉髻) 속에 모든 광명이 담겨 있도다. 자리 옆에서 나는 소리 찾아가니 어인 버드나무 꽂혀있는가. 우뚝한 모습에 깜짝 놀랐더니 완연한 너의 그림자와 형체로다. 삼토(三土)가 거의 다 타게 되었으니 행여나[儻] 단비를 주렴.
    향로봉(香爐峯)부처님의 향이나 시체에서 나오는 물, 그것은 본시 모두 같은 것이다. 오훈(五熏)에 찌던 중생들은 부질없이 구별을 만들어 낸다. 참된 마음이 있어 두루 온 세상을 섭리하도다. 소의 머리에도 전단(栴檀)이 있고 안중(眼中)에도 금설(金屑)이 있다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0540_010_0080&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Praise of Naksan Temple at Northern Mountain
  author: Yu Gyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    THE JEWELED BOTTLE TERRACE

    Within the crown of enlightenment lies all radiance gathered.
    Following the sound that calls beside the seat,
    I find a willow branch gently placed.
    Startled by its noble form—
    It stands complete, your shadow and true image both.
    The three lands grow nearly parched;
    O grant us, if you will, the mercy of soft rain.

    THE INCENSE BURNER PEAK

    The fragrance of Buddha and the water from decay
    are fundamentally one and the same.
    The five perfumes that have steeped all sentient beings
    spawn empty distinctions and false divisions.
    Yet there exists a true mind
    that pervades and governs the great cosmos.
    In the ox's head dwells sandalwood;
    in the eye rests a speck of gold.
  footnotes:
    - The three lands (三土) refer to the realms of dharma in Buddhist cosmology, often understood as the three realms of desire, form, and formlessness.
    - The five perfumes (五熏) are Buddhist incenses—sandalwood, agarwood, camphor, clove, and frankincense—symbolizing the various ways dharma reaches all beings.
    - The references to the ox's head and the eye allude to the Huayan (華嚴) Buddhist teaching that Buddha-nature pervades all things, no matter how humble or refined.
